data.meta_description: Surrounding a cottage on a one-acre block, this garden by Ashley James features a meaningful memorial and a cut-flower garden.
data.text:
When the owners of this Donvale cottage purchased the property, they quickly enlisted the help of garden designer Ashley James to revive its un-loved garden.

As keen gardeners, the couple wanted a space they could enjoy and tinker in when they liked, but something relatively low maintenance that didnâ€™t require them to work on it every day.

â€˜The clients are old family friends from the UK â€” both now retired â€” and they wanted a beautiful garden they could look out on and enjoy from every room in the house.â€™

Re-establishing the landscape was especially important given the homeâ€™s position in the centre of the sloping one-acre block, with stone walls and a staircase in the front yard that leads up to the entrance with a sense of mystery.

Ashley looked to traditional cottage-style gardens for inspiration to create the garden beds, combing plants like Buxus sempervirens (English box), Nepeta â€˜walkers blueâ€™ (catmint) and unique ornamental grasses like Miscanthus (Chinese silver grass) for a modern, whimsical feel.

â€˜The planting palette is a mixture of white, pinks, purples and soft pastels,â€™ he adds. â€˜We also used organic bluestones surrounded by dichondra ground covers and perennial plantings to create romantic walkways throughout the garden.â€™

In the backyard, a lush stretch of lawn meets a wildflower meadow and a cut flower garden that allows the clients to have an endless selection of bright-coloured flowers around their house â€” ranging from Zinnia, to Marigold, or Cornflower, Cosmos, and many more.

With a personal connection to the owners, Ashley says his favourite part of the renewed landscaping is the memorial garden dedicated to their late son.

â€˜Itâ€™s a simple space in the garden with a timber chair (crafted by their son) under the shade of a large tree and surrounded by beautiful perennial plantings and meadow fields,â€™ Ashley explains.
